The first burn victims healing center in the nation is the Firefighters For Healing Center in Downtown Minneapolis. I had the honor of creating a mural for the healing center for burn victims and their families to enjoy. The unique healing center is a space where victims of fire-related injuries and trauma can come and heal with their families. It’s located directly across from the Fairview Hennepin Hospital of Minneapolis and connects via a skyway for easy transit back and forth.

Jake LaFerriere (a former firefighter and burn victim, pictured with me below) and Chris Dunker are the pioneers of the FFFH center. They’ve done tremendous work for firefighters and their communities and now this new healing center is their home and supportive way to continue to give back. The mural reflects Jake’s story and depicts Firefighters, first responders, doctors and neuroses who are all true heroes.

Cycle Minneapolis, NE, Twin Cities, St. Paul & Minnesota

I made a 5-part series of “Cycle ______” screen prints starting in 2007. Cycle Minneapolis was the first in the series for the inaugural @artcrank show at @oneononebike ‘s original location in downtown Minneapolis.

That print was so popular that it sold out at the show. The inspiration for this print was from one of my favorite artists, Alphonse Mucha, who has a style I have always loved. He uses very thick outlines on his main subject matter and has a ton of detail in other elements throughout his compositions. I have based parts of my art career on how I imagine he created work for his clients.  He uses his style to communicate his clients message through advertising. Cycle Minneapolis follows Mucha’s “Cycle Perfecta” composition while bringing a Minneapolis bike-messenger edge to the art.

I over-printed the run and kept a few back. I recently unearthed a few rare first editions and some other editions from my flat file collections. 

They’re up on the site for the bike art nerds that want a rare numbered edition print. 

Stay tuned… I’ll continue to tell stories about each of these prints throughout this week.

#adamturman #turman #artwork #bike #art #screeprinting #cycle #minneapolis #minnesota

Cycle Northeast

This 3-color screen print was originally created for @artcrank ‘s second Minneapolis show in 2008. The concept draws from my 2007 print, Cycle Minneapolis. The big change was that I made it a rare horizontal/landscape orientation… Oooo, I don’t have many prints that are horizontal.

Cycle Northeast also used a tried and true compositional formula that included an emphasis on the main subject, part of a recognizable landscape and words to drive home the concept 😅

After the initial print run had sold out, I reconfigured the layout and turned the horizontal layout into a vertical/portrait orientation so it would match my other prints in my “Cycle ______” screen print series.

I had thought I’d sold out of all of these prints. However I found a few deep in the depths of my flat files. Now available for you and your adorable hands to get a hold of. Link to my site in bio.

Yellow + Blue = Green

We’re nearing the end of @30daysofbiking in April and I got to thinking about the print I made for them in 2013.

This screen print combines 5 blue layers and one yellow layer to create a family of greens in one squeegee pass. You can see the various blue layers in my production file via Photoshop. And you can see how it came to life on the actual print by simply mixing 5 blues to work together and one layer of yellow to create a dynamic effect with just adding one color. Screen printing can be pretty cool.

Also, there are 30 different types of bicycles in this image. That was a lot of research and drawing. Some of my all-time favorite bikes are included.

Ride on!

We had the pleasure of working with artist and muralist @adamturman at the new 3M Skills Development Center in St. Paul, MN. 👏

Right when you walk in the doors of the 3M Skills Development Center, the first thing you’ll see are the bright pops of color, recognizable skylines of the Twin Cities, and of course, 3M – all of which make up Adam’s piece. Aptly titled ‘3M and the Community’, this mural represents 3M’s involvement with the community locally and the many ways the company is reaching communities globally.

“The inspiration for my piece is really about 3M and how they interact and make things that are innovative 𝘧𝘰𝘳 the community and 𝘸𝘪𝘵𝘩 the community,” Turman said.

Adam’s hope for this piece is that you can see yourself in it – whether you’re a shop manager, body technician, or painter – this one’s for 𝘺𝘰𝘶! As we all know, artists have their ‘signature looks’ – for Adam, that’s incorporating many Minnesota-isms and details, including a few ‘Easter eggs’ (you’ll have to stop in and find them all for yourself! 😏).

The 3M Skills Development Center is a space meant for learning, teaching, and creating. We hope this piece inspires that within you!
